It is known that the cell targeting abilities of biocompatible DDSs increase their therapeutic influences against different diseases. Recently, a dopamine functionalized nano-graphene oxide, DA-nGO, system was prepared for the cell delivery of anticancer methotrexate, MTX, drug to human breast adenocarcinoma cells that are dopamine receptor positive [78]. The antineoplastic effect of methotrexate loaded DA-nGO system was examined against DA receptor negative and positive cells and it was found that the DA-functionalized GO enhanced the MTX delivery efficiency for the DA receptor positive cells (Fig. 1
                        ). Additionally, the antineoplastic activities of free MTX as well as the MTX-loaded nGO and DA-nGO were explored toward the DA receptor negative HEK-293 and positive MCF7 cell lines (Fig. 2
                        ). In these tests, equal quantities of unloaded DA-nGO were used as the control to examine the nanocarrier toxicity. It was revealed that although the control unloaded DA-nGO did not indicate substantial cytotoxicity to the HEK-293 and MCF7 cells, the cells treated by high amounts of the MTX, MTX loaded nGO and DA-nGO showed a dose-dependent diminution in the cell viability.

Carbon nanotubes (CNTs) are auspicious nanostructures for biomedicine applications as a result of their outstanding atomic configurations, electronic, mechanical and optical characteristics, high surface area to volume ratios and the functionalization capacity [81]. The CNTs are ultralight tubular nanomaterials having high aspect ratios (length/diameter), rich functional surface chemistry and great payload capability [82]. Appropriately functionalized CNTs are non-immunogenic, biocompatible and photoluminescent. Thus, CNTs can be used as suitable clinical nanocarriers for drug delivery and imaging [83]. For example, batches of oxidized multiwalled carbon nanotubes with different lengths were employed to produce two doxorubicin-loaded drug delivery systems [84]. The two batches were differently internalized onto cell lysates and revealed dissimilar toxicities. The in vitro tests proved that after 48 h of incubation, shorter nanotubes had the superior efficacy. Nonetheless, prolonging the incubation time up to 72 h led to decrease in the efficiency difference because the doxorubicin was released spontaneously from the non-internalized long nanotubes [84]. Also, buckypapers based on diverse types of CNTs were produced with and without adding four model drugs including two alkaline (selegiline hydrochloride, SHC, and clonidine hydrochloride, CHC) and two acidic (ketorolac tromethamine, KT, and flurbiprofen, FB) drugs (see Fig. 3
                        ) and it was found that applying electric biases with suitable polarities could modulate the drug release profile in any preferred direction [85]. The Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) images of the SHC, KT, buckypapers prepared using unloaded and SHC and KT loaded SWCNTs (−COOH) are presented in Fig. 4
                        . The multiwalled carbon nanotubes were decorated with titanium dioxide-gold nanoparticles to deliver the doxorubicin (DOX) drug (Fig. 5
                        ) [86]. The drug nanocarrier (NDC) exhibited improved efficiency for the treatment of MCF7 and A549 cancer cell lines compared to the DOX alone with a very high drug release capacity of 90.66% during 10 h. Figs. 6 and 7

                         illustrate the fluorescence microscopy images of the cell uptake and internalization of DOX and DOX-loaded NDC by the MCF7 and A549 cancer cells.

Biodegradable, chemically cross-linked, stimuli responsive and porous polyacrylamide/dextran, PAM/D, hydrogel nanocomposite was prepared and incorporated with AgNPs [110]. The nanohydrogels exhibited high resistance to Bacillus cereus bacterium (Fig. 11
                        ) indicating they are potential vehicles for drug delivery. The in vitro release of ornidazole drug was 98.5% in 6 h from the hydrogel containing 1.5% Ag NPs (Fig. 12
                        ).

Fig. 25
 displays the in vitro MTT cytotoxicity assay and the in vivo tissue histopathology. The anticancer drug (imatinib) was incorporated into the PUs (94% loading efficiency) and the drug release was examined at diverse pH values. The PUs displayed a sustained release for >300 h. The drug release at physiological pH (7.4) was much less than that measured in the acidic and basic pH amounts. At acidic pH, 82% drug release was observed but it was 41% at physiological pH (Fig. 26
). Hence, such PUs can be applied as smart drug transport platforms in targeted cancer therapy.

Some Fe3O4@ZnO:Er3+,Yb3+@(β-CD) core–shell nanoparticles were prepared as carriers to examine drug loading and controlled release of etoposide (VP-16) chemotherapy agent (Fig. 43
                        ) [268]. The SEM and TEM images of Fe3O4, Fe3O4@ZnO:Er3+,Yb3+ and the Fe3O4@ZnO:Er3+,Yb3+@(β-CD) and their histograms indicating particle size distributions are presented in Fig. 44
                        . The chemically inert β-cyclodextrin cavity stored the etoposide molecules through hydrophobic contacts. The core Fe3O4 was used for magnetic targeting but the shell ZnO:Er3+,Yb3+ was served for fluorescence imaging. Furthermore, the shell ZnO:Er3+,Yb3+ was acted as a suitable microwave absorbing material indicating outstanding microwave thermal response characteristics in the microwave stimulated release of drug. It was shown that the VP-16 release was 18% by the microwave radiation in 15 min but it was 2% after 6 h in absence of microwave radiation. Moreover, the release rate was controlled by changing the number of cycles and time period of microwave irradiation. Hence, such material was produced as a valuable, smart, noninvasive and externally controlled DDS for cancer therapy.
